Page 3: HTTPS & Encryption
HTTPS (Hyper Text Transfer Protocol Secure):
HTTPS comes to overcome the issues of HTTP.
Rather than communicating text in plaintext format, it uses encrypted communication.
"So if any interruption occurs, the data cannot be read because it is in an encrypted format".
HTTPS is built on cryptography protocols: SSL (Secure Socket Layer) and TLS (Transport Layer Security).
These protocols establish an encrypted connection between your browser & the server.
When you visit an HTTPS site, the browser first verifies its SSL certificate to ensure it is legitimate.
This validation allows both parties to establish a secure communication channel.
Security Comparison:
No Secure (HTTP): Sending "HELLO" → "HELLO". An eavesdropper could read it in plain text.
Secure (HTTPS): Sending "HELLO" → Encryption → "EHLLO" → Decryption → "HELLO". No eavesdropping will work because of encryption and decryption.
The CIA Triad in HTTPS:
Confidentiality
Integrity
Authentication

